import DocsLayout from "../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro";
---
<DocsLayout title="Settings — Band Docs">
  <h1>Settings</h1>
  <p>
    The Settings page in Band lets you configure global preferences that apply across all
    projects and workspaces. Access it by clicking the gear icon in the dashboard toolbar
    and selecting <strong>Settings</strong>.
  </p>
  <p>
    Settings are organized into sections. Each section has a dedicated page with a save button.
    A blue indicator dot appears on the save button when you have unsaved changes.
  </p>

  <h2>Appearance</h2>
  <p>
    Controls the visual theme of the Band dashboard:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>System</strong> &mdash; Follows your operating system's light/dark mode preference. Updates automatically when your OS theme changes.</li>
    <li><strong>Light</strong> &mdash; Forces a light color scheme.</li>
    <li><strong>Dark</strong> &mdash; Forces a dark color scheme.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    You can also cycle through themes using the theme toggle button in the dashboard toolbar
    without opening Settings.
  </p>

  <h2>General</h2>
  <p>
    The General section contains core configuration:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Worktrees folder</strong> &mdash; The directory where new git worktrees are created.
      Defaults to <code>~/.band/worktrees</code>. You can change this to any directory, for example
      if you want worktrees on a faster drive or a specific location. Use the browse button to
      pick a folder via the native file picker.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Labels</h2>
  <p>
    Labels let you organize projects into color-coded groups. From this section you can:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Add labels</strong> &mdash; Click the <strong>Add label</strong> button to create a new label with a default name and color.</li>
    <li><strong>Edit labels</strong> &mdash; Change the name and color of any existing label. Click the color swatch to open a color picker.</li>
    <li><strong>Delete labels</strong> &mdash; Click the trash icon to remove a label. Projects assigned to a deleted label become unlabeled.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Once labels are created, assign them to projects via the right-click context menu on any
    project name in the dashboard. Use the label filter in the toolbar to show only projects
    with a specific label.
  </p>

  <h2>Coding Agents</h2>
  <p>
    Configure the coding agents available on your machine. The list is auto-populated
    on first launch by detecting installed CLIs (currently <code>claude</code>,
    <code>codex</code>, and <code>opencode</code>). You can add or remove entries
    at any time, and pick which one is the default for new chat panes.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Coding agents list</strong> &mdash; Each entry has an <code>id</code>,
      a <code>type</code> (one of <code>claude-code</code>, <code>cursor-cli</code>,
      <code>openai-codex</code>, <code>codex</code>, <code>gemini-cli</code>,
      <code>opencode</code>), a display <code>label</code>, and optional
      <code>command</code> and <code>model</code> overrides.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Default coding agent</strong> &mdash; The <code>id</code> of the entry
      used for new chat panes when no per-pane override is set. Each chat pane can
      override the agent, model, or mode at creation time.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Command</strong> (optional, per agent) &mdash; A custom executable path
      or command for that agent, e.g.
      <code>claude --dangerously-skip-permissions</code>. Leave empty to use the
      default binary the adapter detects on <code>PATH</code>.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Notifications</h2>
  <p>
    Configure audio notifications for agent events:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Notification sound toggle</strong> &mdash; Enable or disable playing a sound when an agent transitions from working to needs attention.</li>
    <li><strong>Sound selection</strong> &mdash; Choose from several built-in sounds. Selecting a sound plays a preview so you can hear it before saving.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Web Server</h2>
  <p>
    Configure the Band web server that powers the dashboard and provides the API:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Port</strong> &mdash; The port the web server listens on. Defaults to <code>3456</code>. Changing this requires a restart.</li>
    <li><strong>Auto-start tunnel</strong> &mdash; When enabled, automatically starts a remote tunnel when the app launches, making your Band instance accessible from mobile devices or other machines.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Settings Storage</h2>
  <p>
    All settings are persisted in <code>~/.band/settings.json</code>. You can view the current
    settings via the CLI:
  </p>
  <pre><code>band settings              # pretty-printed JSON
band settings --output json # machine-readable JSON (no trailing newline)</code></pre>
  <p>
    While you can edit the file directly, it is recommended to use the Settings UI to avoid
    malformed JSON or invalid values.
  </p>
</DocsLayout>
